# [[in]]; [[at]]; [[on]]; {{n-g|locative case marker, attested primarily in ''[[w:hyangga|hyangga]]'' poems}}
#* {{quote-book|oko|year=c. 750|author={{lw|ko|월명사|月明師|tr=Wolmyeongsa}}|chapter={{lw|ko|제망매가|祭亡妹歌|tr=Jemangmae-ga}}|title={{lw|ko|三國遺事|三國遺事|tr=Samguk Yusa}}|trans-title={{w|Samguk Yusa|Memorabilia of the Three Kingdoms}}|text=一等隱枝'''良'''出古|t=even though they sprout '''on''' a single branch|tr=*HAton KACI-'''a''' NA-kwo}}

=====Usage notes=====
* First-millennium Old Korean also featured the locative particle {{m|oko|中|tr=*-kuy}}. The two particles were compounded as {{m|oko|良中|tr=*-a-kuy}} as early as the seventh century. The compounded form becomes predominant in the corpus after the eleventh century, after which {{m|oko|良|tr=*-a}} in isolation is not encountered. The compounded form eventually fused into a single morpheme, becoming the Middle Korean locative particle {{m|okm|-에|-에〮/애〮|tr=-éy/áy}}.
* After the fourteenth century, Korean scribes occasionally reused the character {{m|okm|良}} to write {{m|okm|-에|-에〮/애〮|tr=-éy/áy}}. This is a feature of Middle Korean writing, not Old Korean.

